    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Colt Keith** (63.01) and **Trea Turner** (62.67) serving as our undisputed pillars. **Colt Keith** benefits from a strong park factor and a favorable matchup against Sproat, while **Trea Turner** remains the engine of our offensive production; his lead-off spot against Cabrera provides the ideal environment for the stolen base opportunities we prioritize given our league\u2019s scarcity. **Kyle Schwarber** (59.51) sits just outside the elite tier, but his xwOBA of .402 and the second-spot protection behind the top of the order make him a high-floor start despite a mediocre matchup against Cabrera. Meanwhile, **Caleb Durbin** (50.73) continues to offer reliable efficiency, overcoming a suboptimal #8 lineup slot through solid base projection and park-adjusted scoring.\n\nOur most difficult roster decision involved **Carson Benge** (38.70), who fell just shy of our 40.0-point threshold for active duty. While **Carson Benge** brings a solid base, the combination of facing Ryan and a bottom-of-the-order assignment suppressed his ceiling enough to keep him on the bench. We are proceeding cautiously with **Gary Sanchez** (45.85) and **Hyeseong Kim** (41.34); **Gary Sanchez** is staring down an elite assignment against Skubal, which severely limits his efficiency, while **Hyeseong Kim** carries a slight risk due to the opposing catcher's elite pop time, though his aggressive base-running remains a secondary asset against the slow delivery of Webb. \n\nRisks today are concentrated in our catching and middle infield depth. We are monitoring **Gary Sanchez** closely, as the matchup against a 2.71 xERA arm like Skubal leaves him strictly as a volume start rather than a high-ceiling one. With **Yordan Alvarez** and **Junior Caminero** sidelined by off-days, and **Pete Crow-Armstrong** out of the starting lineup entirely, we are relying on the consistency of our primary starters to bridge the gap. We continue to monitor the status of **Christian Yelich**, **Kazuma Okamoto**, **Victor Scott II**, **Zac Veen**, **Luke Raley**, **Lars Nootbaar**, **Jerar Encarnacion**, and **Luis Pena** for upcoming shifts, but for today, the Zebras\u2019 objective remains aggressive base-path pressure from our top-third hitters to compensate for the tougher SP matchups on the docket.",
